From Roger De Abreu Subject Re good and for windows In article Kan Mongwa writes In article Kan Mongwa writes Do not load if you are using this applies for windows I replied Why Do you mean just use in Roger You answered Quoting from windows Under the section for using stacker best performance do not use SMARTDrive to cache the compressed You only need to cache the uncompressed Check it out for yourself I think it is important to clear up your first You gave the impression that you should not use smartdrive with You are correct re caching the compressed However as I understand it you can cache the uncompressed Thus if you have compressed your disk C you will have a C and probably a D drive under C being the compressed disk which is just a large file on D and D being the uncompressed You should only attempt to stack D In fact with Win and it seems smart enough to automatically default to stacking your A B and D Roger